    description2: `Seventy-ninth day of the war. Monday. As I returned from duty, on the stretch of my small radius, the Neva embankment, I could feel the uneven pulsing of the life of the city. The Nikolayevsky Bridge was drawn up. There was traffic only across the Palace Bridge alone. Therefore, the deserted Universitetskaya Embankment turned into a highway. Soon a ship - a gunboat with two long-range guns - appeared between the raised drawn parts of the beautiful bridge. The ship was coming up the Neva. The river was lively. Military shipping boats were stirring the leaden September Neva waters.... Not far from the Palace Bridge the ship stopped and gave a prolonged whistle to be let on sooner. A detachment of sailors in marching uniforms and helmets on marching bags walked along the embankment. Some car, all covered with mud, with broken glass rolled past. In Rumyantsevsky Square again groups of Leningraders were waiting for labour conscription. Armed and unarmed workers were going somewhere in buses.... So suddenly my deserted road along the bed of flowers and bushes was filled with life, like a river in a flood.... By the way, they were trimmed the other day. Someone is looking after them even on these dreadful days! It somehow strengthened me, cheered me up.<br> People are crowding at the gates of the barracks on the Syezdovskaya line. They are waiting to see the wounded stationed there. Some peep into the windows, from where Red Army men and sailors with bandaged heads or hands stick out ...<br> At 7.30 in the evening, when I was resting, suddenly our whole house shook. There was shooting from anti-aircraft guns and machine guns. The first moment was terrifying. But I immediately pulled myself together, overcoming the first urge to leave, to run away from danger..... In the courtyard crowded people at the bomb shelter. Kraush had brought her sick child there. Everyone was looking at the sky. Neighbours came to say that from their windows to the south they could see a huge glow and columns of thick smoke that covered the whole sky. Indeed, when I went to look - behind the Neva a fire was burning. Even in the water it was reflected. Some speculated that the German bombers who had broken through had managed to set fire to oil storage tanks somewhere near Volkov Village....<br> 10 hours and 30 minutes. Another alarm. Went out on the stairs. Searchlights search the sky. Anti-aircraft guns are firing. Returned to my office and I sit in my coat, cap and overshoes under the hood of my green lamp and write .... M. F. makes jokes, "You are just like Archimedes." The house shudders, but not like the other day. Before the alarm I had time to call the service. All the men on duty were ready there. M.F. and I had dinner. We collected our bundles of things and money. M.F. went to her sanitary post.<br> 12 hours and 30 minutes. The alarm continues. Shots are heard occasionally from the ships on the Neva. The neighbours have not yet returned, sitting on the steps of the stairs below. The whole of Leningrad apparently will not sleep tonight.<br> So, on the seventy-ninth day of the war, the bombing of Leningrad began. Ahead, perhaps, there will be many more such anxious nights. The cup of trials will have to be drunk to the bottom, a difficult cup.`,
